  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers in Queensland residential strata buildings deal with a body corporate committee, a set of by-laws, and a sinking fund levy. That is the familiar framework. But owners in certain mixed-use developments face an additional registered document that governs the building: a building management statement. If your lot is in a building with a BMS, understanding what it is and what it means for your sale is worth the time before you go to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a building management statement is</h2>
      <p>A building management statement is a registered document under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld) that applies to buildings containing both community title lots and other lots, such as commercial tenancies, a hotel, a car park, or retail space. It governs the relationship between different title holders who share infrastructure within the same building structure.</p>

      <p>The BMS sets out the rights and obligations of each party in relation to shared infrastructure: access to common areas, maintenance responsibilities for plant and equipment that serves multiple parts of the building, cost apportionment for shared services, and dispute resolution processes between the different title holders. It is not the same as a body corporate by-law, which governs the residential strata scheme in isolation. The BMS operates at a layer above that, dealing with the interface between the different ownership structures within the same building.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a BMS applies</h2>
      <p>A building management statement is most common in mixed-use inner-city developments: residential apartments above retail or commercial floors, hotel-residential towers where lots are sold separately to individual investors, and complexes that combine residential community title with commercial title lots in the same structure.</p>

      <p>Purely residential strata buildings, including most apartment complexes in Brisbane's inner east, typically do not have a BMS. The BMS becomes relevant when a building combines community title lots with other title types. In Brisbane's inner city and near-city suburbs, newer mixed-use developments in areas like Newstead, Fortitude Valley, Teneriffe, and West End are the most likely candidates. If you own a lot in a building that has retail, office, or hotel components on other floors or in an adjoining title structure, checking whether a BMS applies to your lot is a reasonable first step.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the BMS appears in a sale transaction</h2>
      <p>A building management statement is a registered encumbrance on the title. It will appear on a title search of your lot. When a buyer's solicitor conducts due diligence, they will identify the BMS in the title search and will request a copy as part of their review. In a well-prepared sale, the BMS should be sourced and available before the contract is signed rather than surfaced as a due diligence item during the cooling-off period.</p>

      <p>A copy of the BMS can be obtained through a title search with the Queensland Titles Registry. Your body corporate manager should also hold a copy, since the BMS directly affects the body corporate's obligations to parties outside the scheme. Your solicitor can assist with obtaining a current, certified copy for disclosure purposes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should disclose</h2>
      <p>Queensland's property contract framework requires sellers to disclose encumbrances on the title. A registered BMS is an encumbrance, so its existence must be disclosed in the contract. The standard REIQ contract form includes a section for registered encumbrances. Your solicitor will handle the specific drafting, but you should be aware that non-disclosure of a registered encumbrance can give a buyer grounds to rescind a contract in certain circumstances.</p>

      <p>Beyond the document itself, buyers will want to know whether there are any current disputes under the BMS, any outstanding obligations the lot is subject to under the BMS, and whether maintenance obligations under the BMS are being met or have unresolved arrears. If there are active disputes between the residential body corporate and another title holder under the BMS, that is material information. Your solicitor will advise on what needs to be disclosed in your specific situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers are likely to ask</h2>
      <p>A buyer's solicitor reviewing a BMS will look at the cost-sharing arrangements for shared services, any restrictions on use or access that affect the residential lot, the termination or amendment provisions, and whether any obligations run with the land rather than the current owner. A well-drafted BMS with clear cost-sharing provisions and no active disputes will typically not slow a sale. An older BMS with ambiguous terms or a building where the BMS obligations have been poorly managed can attract additional scrutiny and may affect how buyers price the risk into their offer.</p>

      <p>For sellers in inner Brisbane mixed-use buildings, the practical advice is straightforward: identify whether a BMS applies before you list, obtain a current copy, ask your body corporate manager whether there are any active disputes or unresolved obligations under it, and make sure your solicitor is briefed. None of this is complicated if it is handled in the preparation phase rather than during the campaign.</p>

